## 3. How Users Are Expected to Interact with Secured Endpoints

### Step-by-step user journey:

```
┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  1. REGISTER                                               │
│  POST /api/v1/auth/register                                │
│  Body: { username, password, email, name }                 │
│  → Returns { accessToken, refreshToken }                   │
│  → User created with Role.USER (no special permissions)    │
├────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  2. LOGIN (subsequent sessions)                            │
│  POST /api/v1/auth/login                                   │
│  Body: { username, password }                              │
│  → Returns { accessToken, refreshToken }                   │
│  → All previous tokens revoked                             │
├────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  3. ACCESS SECURED ENDPOINTS                               │
│  Header: Authorization: Bearer <accessToken>               │
│                                                             │
│  • /users/current (GET/PATCH)  → any authenticated user    │
│  • /users/** (CRUD)            → @PreAuthorize("hasRole('ADMIN')") │
│  • /management/**              → hasRole(ADMIN|MANAGER)    │
│                                                             │
│  The AuthenticationFilter validates the token on every      │
│  request (signature, expiry, not revoked in DB).           │
├────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  4. REFRESH WHEN TOKEN EXPIRES                             │
│  POST /api/v1/auth/refresh-token                           │
│  Header: Authorization: Bearer <refreshToken>              │
│  → Returns a fresh { accessToken, refreshToken }           │
├────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  5. ROLE ELEVATION (admin operation)                       │
│  POST /api/v1/auth/authorize                               │
│  Header: Authorization: Bearer <admin-accessToken>         │
│  Body: { username, role: "ADMIN", secret: "<auth-key>" }   │
│  → Upgrades the target user's role, returns new tokens     │
├────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  6. LOGOUT                                                 │
│  POST /api/v1/auth/logout                                  │
│  Header: Authorization: Bearer <accessToken>               │
│  → Revokes the token in DB, clears SecurityContext         │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

### Additional protective layers:

| Layer | How it Works |
|-------|-------------|
| **Password Encoding** | BCrypt via `BCryptPasswordEncoder` — passwords are never stored in plain text. |
| **Token Revocation** | Access tokens are persisted in the `TOKEN` table with `expired` and `revoked` flags. On login/refresh, all prior tokens for that user are revoked. On logout, the current token is revoked. The `AuthenticationFilter` checks these flags on every request. |
| **Rate Limiting** | Annotation-driven (`@RateLimit`, `@RateLimitCategory`). The `/auth/**` endpoints default to 5 requests/minute; standard endpoints default to 60 req/min. Prevents brute-force attacks. |
| **Idempotency** | `@Idempotent` annotation on mutating endpoints (e.g., register, create user). Clients must send an `Idempotency-Key` header. Redis-backed deduplication prevents replay/double-submit attacks. |
| **CSRF** | Disabled (appropriate for a stateless JWT API that never uses cookies). |
| **Session** | Stateless (`SessionCreationPolicy.STATELESS`) — no server-side HTTP session is created. |
| **Correlation ID** | Every request gets an `X-Correlation-ID` header (or auto-generates one), propagated in MDC logs, enabling audit trails. |
| **401 Handling** | Custom `AuthenticationEntryPoint` returns a structured JSON error (`BaseResponse` + `GenericErrorMessage`) instead of the default Spring HTML error page. |
| **Actuator** | Health details are shown only `when-authorized`, and the `/actuator/**` path is publicly accessible (but sensitive details require authentication). |

